===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|threte}}, {{m|enm|thret}}, {{m|enm|thrat}}, {{m|enm|thræt}}, {{m|enm|threat}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|þrēat||crowd, swarm, troop, army, press; pressure, trouble, calamity, oppression, force, violence, threat}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*þrautaz}}, closely tied to {{etyl|gem-pro|-}} {{m|gem-pro|*þrautą||displeasure, complaint, grievance, labour, toil}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*trewd-||to squeeze, push, press}}, whence also Middle Low German {{m|gml|drōt||threat, menace, danger}}, Middle High German {{m|gmh|drōz||annoyance, disgust, horror, terror, fright}}, Icelandic {{m|is|þraut||struggle, labour, distress}}, Latin {{m|la|trūdere||to push}}.

